Family was here several years ago and we thought the experience was mediocre at best. We keep strictly kosher so options are often limited. We recently visited Orlando and tried again as there are not many other choices near by. Due to covid there was a long line to get in since the restaurant was not seating every table for safety. We debated leaving but are very glad we waited!!  We all decided on what we wanted while on line and once we got seated we immediately ordered to save on time.  To our amazement based on how busy they were and on typically less then great kosher dining service experienes we have had outside of big cities like NY and LA, the food was served really fast!!  The staff was pleasant despite being slammed. Most importantly the food was far better than anyone in the family remembers from our prior trip.  Not sure what changed since then, new chef, new management, new owner, plain good luck, but whatever the reason it was great.  My family and I will be very eager to dine again in the future, something I never imagined saying several years ago from our prior experience. I definitely recommend giving them another look.  Lastly I was amazed how good the Asian noodle dish was. First surprised it was on the otherwise mostly middle eastern menu and more importantly it was so good it beats out similar dishes I have had at Asian only kosher cuisine in general.  Hope your next visit to Kosher Grill will be as enjoyable

The food is good, with good taste. We have been there many times over the years, ordering dine-in and also takeout. When the restaurant is above a certain number of customers that’s when you may have issues. There’s no proper “hostess” or “welcome service”.  We have been left waiting for way longer than the “hostess” told us the waiting time would be. Wait lines are not organized in any way and with cars moving around just outside the restaurant it may be risky for kids. In our last visit the hostess allowed at least two family of “friends” (or someone she knew, at least) cut in front of us. When my wife complained with her she tried to bully my wife into being quiet which is unacceptable. If you don’t know how to deal with unhappy customers then don’t be in the customer hospitality business. During this exchange of words between the hostess and my wife one of my daughters tripped, felt and hit the restaurant glass very hard with her forehead. The host was indifferent about it, kept trying to explain why we were wrong in complaining and she was right about people cutting in front of us. She only realized she should have tried to offer any help for our daughter with a big bump in her head when we had left and were entering our car, but still very defensive saying we scream for no reason. At this point I had to shout and ask her to shut up and just go away. She was being confrontational and exposing my kids to more undue stress. Unfortunately this place is the only fleishik restaurant in Orlando. I would eat a canned tuna sandwich at the hotel to avoid the stress of dealing of the hostess of this restaurant at any time where there’s more people than maybe a handful of tables.
